DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(75)90013-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0022199675900136
AB  - The paper analyzes the classic question: Is there a presumption as to the direction the terms of trade will change when one country makes a transfer to another? The model incorporates nontraded commodities. The presumption is shown to depend upon (1) the causes of trade, whether due to differences in demand or supply, and (2) the sensitivity to price changes of demanders as opposed to suppliers.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - The welfare loss of negative value-added
AU  - Michaely, Michael
JO  - Journal of International Economics
VL  - 5
IS  - 3
SP  - 283
EP  - 287
PY  - 1975
DA  - 1975/08/01/
SN  - 0022-1996
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0022-1996(75)90015-X
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/002219967590015X
AB  - This brief paper applies the ‘triangles’ method of measurement of the cost of protection to an industry with negative value-added in international prices. The production loss cannot be estimated in this case by the normal procedure, which utilizes the effective protective rate: the latter is negative, when defined in the conventional way, and is thus useless for the purpose on hand. The production loss is separated into two components: the negative value-added itself — the foreign-exchange loss; and payments to domestic productive factors — the domestic resource loss. Despite the fact that the effective protective rate as such does not appear in the formula for the estimation of the production loss, this loss is presented as, among other things, a rising function of the output duties and of input coefficients and as a declining function of input duties — all the ingredients which make the effective rate of protection.
ER  - 

